<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1862-08-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1862-08-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="302" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d302">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Dayton</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 196.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1862-08-09"><hi rend="italic">August</hi> 9, 1862.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            despatch (No. 176) of the 24th ultimo, accompanied by a copy of your
                            letter of the 15th ultimo to our consul at Marseilles in regard to the
                            case of one Gauthreaux, a destitute citizen of the United States, and to
                            the support of paupers from the United States in foreign countries and
                                <hi rend="italic">vice versa</hi>. The views expressed in that
                            letter are entirely approved.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">William L. Dayton</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>